13 Throughput calculation in RAID 0
Let \(n\) be the number of volumes used to store a quantity of data \(D\) involved in an I/O operation, and let’s assume for simplicity that they are equally distributed across the \(n\) units, so that each of them contains exactly \(\frac{D}{n}\) data.
The average throughput \(\tau_m\) will be given by the ratio between the total memory \(D\) occupied by the data and the sum of the times with which the individual disks perform a read/write operation:
\[
\tau_m=\frac{D}{\sum\limits_{i=1}^nt_i}
\]
The time \(t_i\) is given by the ratio between the amount of data on a disk, which is \(\frac{D}{n}\), and the throughput of the relative disk:
\[
t_i=\frac{D}{n\tau_i}
\]
From which follows
\[
\tau_m=\frac{\cancel{D}}{\frac{\cancel{D}}{n}\sum\limits_{i=1}^n\frac{1}{\tau_i}}=\frac{n}{\frac{1}{\tau_1}+\frac{1}{\tau_2}+\dots+\frac{1}{\tau_n}}=\frac{n\tau_1\tau_2\dots\tau_n}{\tau_2\tau_3\dots\tau_n+\tau_1\tau_3\dots\tau_n+\dots+\tau_1\tau_2\dots\tau_{n-1}}
\]
Which expressed in a compact way will be
\[
\hspace{2cm}
    \tau_m=\frac{n\prod\limits_{i=1}^n\tau_i}{\sum\limits_{i=1}^n\left(\prod\limits_{\substack{j=0 \ j\neq i}}^{n}\tau_j\right)}
    \hspace{0.5cm}
    \Longrightarrow
    \hspace{-3.5cm}
    \begin{split}
        &n=2 \ \rightarrow \ \tau_m=\frac{n\tau_1\tau_2}{\tau_1+\tau_2}\\
        &n=3 \ \rightarrow \ \tau_m=\frac{n\tau_1\tau_2\tau_3}{\tau_1\tau_2+\tau_1\tau_3+\tau_2\tau_3}\\
        &\dots
    \end{split}
\]
